rious Violence Bill to introduce a new legal duty on public bodies to prevent and tackle serious violence.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","4941","2019-11-01T12:01:35.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156202/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156202/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-24","Knives: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of trends in the level of knife crime in (a) London and (b) England.","false","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","Bexleyheath and Crayford","Sir David Evennett","4942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156203","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-11-01","<p>Theft of a pet is already a criminal offence punishable by a penalty of up to 7 years imprisonment. In February 2016, the independent Sentencing Council updated its guidelines in relation to sentencing for theft offences. The guidelines take account of the emotional distress, and therefore harm, that the theft of a much beloved pet can have on the victim, and accordingly recommend higher penalties for such offences.</p>","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith",,"2019-11-01T17:23:17.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156203/answer","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156203/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-24","Pets: Theft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of making pet theft a specific crime.","false","Biography information for Alberto Costa","South Leicestershire","Alberto Costa","5044"
