"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156205","Home Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>The Home Office collects data from forces on the number of individuals released on pre-charge bail. The most recent statistics were published on 24 October 2019 <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-powers-and-procedures-england-and-wales-year-ending-31-march-2019" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-powers-and-procedures-england-and-wales-year-ending-31-march-2019</a>. Due to data quality issues, these statistics can give an indicative picture only, and should be treated with caution. Figures suggest 86,600 individuals were released on pre-charge bail year ending 31 March 2019.</p><p>Work is ongoing to improve this data collection, and to explore a separate but complementary collection on released under investigation.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2019-11-05T12:49:59.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156205/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156205/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-24","Criminal Investigation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans the Government has to collect data on the category of offences for people released under investigation.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","5053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156206","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-29","<p>The Department takes seriously the need to support vulnerable claimants, and wants the application process for Universal Credit to be as quick and easy as possible, ensuring that claimants receive money at the earliest opportunity. It is designed to be a ‘digital-first’ service, ensuring we make best use of technology to deliver a modern and effective working-age welfare system, allowing our staff to concentrate on those people who require additional support.</p><p> </p><p>We are already committed to placing Universal Credit guidance in the House’s Library and last updated it on 28 March 2019.</p><p> </p><p>Our Universal Credit Claimant Survey, found that 98 per cent of claimants have internet access and did claim online, and the majority of those said they found the claim process overall to be straightforward. This can be accessed at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-credit-full-service-claimant-survey" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-credit-full-service-claimant-survey</a></p><p> </p><p>All Jobcentre Plus offices across the country have Wi-Fi and computers available for claimants to access the internet. For those that are still unable to access or use digital services, or are not able to travel, assistance to make and maintain their claim is available via the Freephone Universal Credit helpline – which is clearly displayed on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p>Citizens Advice and Citizens Advice Scotland have been delivering the ‘Help to Claim’ service on a pilot basis since April 2019. The Citizens Advice Help to Claim service offers tailored, practical support to help people make a Universal Credit claim up to receiving their first full correct payment on time, and is available online, on the phone and face-to-face through local Citizen’s Advice services.</p><p> </p><p>Although the Department offers comprehensive support for claimants to use our digital service, there will be occasions when people are unable to make their claim online, and so telephone applications can be accepted. In these instances, information normally available through a claimant’s online account, will be communicated in an alternative format which is best suited to an individual’s circumstances.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince","5095 ; 5097 ; 5098","2019-10-29T16:42:10.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156206/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156206/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-24","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether people are entitled to claim universal credit by telephone; and if she will place in the Library a copy of her Department's internal guidance for staff on accepting telephone claims for universal credit.","false","Biography information for Laura Pidcock","North West Durham","Laura Pidcock","5094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156207","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-29","<p>The Department takes seriously the need to support vulnerable claimants, and wants the application process for Universal Credit to be as quick and easy as possible, ensuring that claimants receive money at the earliest opportunity. It is designed to be a ‘digital-first’ service, ensuring we make best use of technology to deliver a modern and effective working-age welfare system, allowing our staff to concentrate on those people who require additional support.</p><p> </p><p>We are already committed to placing Universal Credit guidance in the House’s Library and last updated it on 28 March 2019.</p><p> </p><p>Our Universal Credit Claimant Survey, found that 98 per cent of claimants have internet access and did claim online, and the majority of those said they found the claim process overall to be straightforward. This can be accessed at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-credit-full-service-claimant-survey" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-credit-full-service-claimant-survey</a></p><p> </p><p>All Jobcentre Plus offices across the country have Wi-Fi and computers available for claimants to access the internet. For those that are still unable to access or use digital services, or are not able to travel, assistance to make and maintain their claim is available via the Freephone Universal Credit helpline – which is clearly displayed on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p>Citizens Advice and Citizens Advice Scotland have been delivering the ‘Help to Claim’ service on a pilot basis since April 2019. The Citizens Advice Help to Claim service offers tailored, practical support to help people make a Universal Credit claim up to receiving their first full correct payment on time, and is available online, on the phone and face-to-face through local Citizen’s Advice services.</p><p> </p><p>Although the Department offers comprehensive support for claimants to use our digital service, there will be occasions when people are unable to make their claim online, and so telephone applications can be accepted. In these instances, information normally available through a claimant’s online account, will be communicated in an alternative format which is best suited to an individual’s circumstances.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince","5094 ; 5097 ; 5098","2019-10-29T16:42:10.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156207/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156207/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-24","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what guidance her Department has issued on making a claim for universal credit by telephone.","false","Biography information for Laura Pidcock","North West Durham","Laura Pidcock","5095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156208","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-29","<p>In February-April 2010 there were 9.5 million economically inactive people in the UK. This number has dropped to 8.7 million people for the period June-August 2019. These statistics are for the 16-64 age group, which is the Office for National Statistic’s headline rate for economic inactivity.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2019-10-29T16:34:09.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156208/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156208/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-24","Unemployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people were economically inactive in the UK in (a) 2010 and (b) the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","4934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156209","Department for Education","false","2019-11-01","<p>Since 18 September 2017, data on Sure Start children’s centres has been supplied by local authorities via the department’s Get Information about Schools database portal at: <a href="https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/</a>.</p><p>Based on information supplied by local authorities as at end June 2019, the number of children’s centres open to families and children each year and the number of children’s centres closed each year since 2010 is set out in the attached table[1]:</p><p> </p><p>[1]Figures in the table are based on information supplied by local authorities as at end June 2019. Since local authorities can update historical data at any time, figures may be different to previous answers, and are likely to change again in future. (Closures reported since June 2019 have not been included in the table to enable consistency with a statistical publication with further analysis of children’s centre numbers, which is due to be published on 7 November – for completeness a total of 9 closures have not been included in the table.) The department holds some of its information on children’s centre numbers for previous years manually. The numbers of children’s centres open each year have been treated as estimates and rounded to the nearest 10.</p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan",,"2019-11-01T11:44:18.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156209/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156209/answer","4935_table_showing_children's_centres_opened_and_closed_since_2010.doc","4935_table_showing_children's_centres_opened_and_closed_since_2010.doc","4935_table","4935_table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156209/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-24","Children's Centres: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many Sure Start centres have closed in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","4935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156210","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-11-01","<p>The independent Office for National Statistics (ONS) uses the Labour Force Survey (LFS) to provide estimates for the usual weekly hours of work for people. The table below sets out data ONS publishes on those working fewer than 6 hours, and between 6 and 15 hours. Breakdowns for Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland, and regional breakdowns, are not provided because of small sample sizes. Estimates are based on the number of people who report the numbers of hours worked.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Table: People working fewer than 6 hours, and 6 to 15 hours for April to June each year</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>fewer than 6 Hours</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>6 up to 15 hours</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>level (thousands)</p></td><td><p>% of total people in employment</p></td><td><p>level (thousands)</p></td><td><p>% of total people in employment</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr-Jun 2010</p></td><td><p>417</p></td><td><p>1.5</p></td><td><p>2,011</p></td><td><p>7.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr-Jun 2011</p></td><td><p>473</p></td><td><p>1.7</p></td><td><p>1,959</p></td><td><p>6.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr-Jun 2012</p></td><td><p>469</p></td><td><p>1.6</p></td><td><p>2,034</p></td><td><p>7.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr-Jun 2013</p></td><td><p>445</p></td><td><p>1.5</p></td><td><p>2,033</p></td><td><p>7.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr-Jun 2014</p></td><td><p>463</p></td><td><p>1.6</p></td><td><p>2,034</p></td><td><p>6.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr-Jun 2015</p></td><td><p>487</p></td><td><p>1.6</p></td><td><p>1,899</p></td><td><p>6.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr-Jun 2016</p></td><td><p>474</p></td><td><p>1.5</p></td><td><p>2,058</p></td><td><p>6.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr-Jun 2017</p></td><td><p>424</p></td><td><p>1.4</p></td><td><p>2,048</p></td><td><p>6.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr-Jun 2018</p></td><td><p>426</p></td><td><p>1.4</p></td><td><p>2,043</p></td><td><p>6.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr-Jun 2019</p></td><td><p>471</p></td><td><p>1.5</p></td><td><p>2,066</p></td><td><p>6.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Table HOUR02NSA, ONS, Labour Force Survey</p><p> </p><p>At UK level people in full-time work have made up over three quarters of the overall increase in employment since 2010.</p><p> </p><p />","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2019-11-01T12:53:53.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156210/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156210/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-24","Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the number of people that worked less than 15 hours a week in each (a) country and (b) region of the UK in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","4936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156211","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-11-04","<p>The independent Office for National Statistics (ONS) use the Labour Force Survey (LFS) to provide estimates for the number of people in employment on contracts that do not guarantee minimum hours (known as ‘zero hours’ contracts’). This data is available for the Oct-Dec quarter only for each year from 2010 to 2018 and is set out in the table below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Table: Level and rate of people aged 16 and over on zero-hours contracts October to December each year</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>UK, not seasonally adjusted</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Percentage of people in employment on a zero-hours contract</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>0.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>0.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>0.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>1.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>2.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>2.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018</p></td><td><p>2.6</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Source: ONS Labour Force Survey</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>The estimates for 2015, 2016, 2017 and 2018 are considered precise</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>ONS advise that the increased media coverage of zero-hours’ contracts arrangements in the latter half of 2013 may have affected the response to this question by raising awareness of this existing type of contractual arrangement. The ONS therefore advise not to compare pre- and post-2013 data.</p><p> </p><p>Data for England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales and the English regions has been published every six months by ONS for since 2016. However, because the data is drawn from a survey, many of these sub-UK breakdowns are considered too unreliable for practical purposes. Regional data and guidance on its reliability can be found in tab 4 of table EMP17 published here:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/datasets/emp17peopleinemploymentonzerohourscontracts/current" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/datasets/emp17peopleinemploymentonzerohourscontracts/current</a></p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2019-11-04T18:38:37.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156211/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156211/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-24","Zero Hours Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the number of people employed on zero-hour contracts in each (a) nation and (b) region of the UK in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","4937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156212","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-29","<p>Service centre calls are recorded and retained for a period of 14 months; this includes inbound and outbound calls to and from UC telephony service centres and any transfers within the service centres.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2019-10-29T11:52:00.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156212/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156212/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-24","Universal Credit: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Answer of 3 April 2019 to Question 238679 on Universal Credit: Telephone Services, whether calls which are transferred to a different case manager or helpline advisor continue to be (a) recorded and (b) retrievable; and what steps she is taking to ensure that all calls on universal credit are recorded to maintain a complete record of a claimant's interactions with the Department.","false","Biography information for Laura Pidcock","North West Durham","Laura Pidcock","5096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156213","Department for International Trade","false","2019-10-29","<p>Scotch whisky is a significant contributor to the UK’s overall food and drink exports. In 2018, whisky exports reached a record £4.8bn, representing over 21% of total food and drink exports. This is an increase of 9.1% on 2017. The largest export market, USA, recorded export sales of £1.06bn, an increase of 12.4%.</p>","Bournemouth West","Conor Burns",,"2019-10-29T10:09:56.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156213/answer","Biography information for Conor Burns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156213/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-10-24","Whisky: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what recent assessment he has made of the contribution of the Scotch whisky industry to the UK's food and drink exports.","false","Biography information for Martin Whitfield","East Lothian","Martin Whitfield","5082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156214","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-29","<p>The Department takes seriously the need to support vulnerable claimants, and wants the application process for Universal Credit to be as quick and easy as possible, ensuring that claimants receive money at the earliest opportunity. It is designed to be a ‘digital-first’ service, ensuring we make best use of technology to deliver a modern and effective working-age welfare system, allowing our staff to concentrate on those people who require additional support.</p><p> </p><p>We are already committed to placing Universal Credit guidance in the House’s Library and last updated it on 28 March 2019.</p><p> </p><p>Our Universal Credit Claimant Survey, found that 98 per cent of claimants have internet access and did claim online, and the majority of those said they found the claim process overall to be straightforward. This can be accessed at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-credit-full-service-claimant-survey" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-credit-full-service-claimant-survey</a></p><p> </p><p>All Jobcentre Plus offices across the country have Wi-Fi and computers available for claimants to access the internet. For those that are still unable to access or use digital services, or are not able to travel, assistance to make and maintain their claim is available via the Freephone Universal Credit helpline – which is clearly displayed on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p>Citizens Advice and Citizens Advice Scotland have been delivering the ‘Help to Claim’ service on a pilot basis since April 2019. The Citizens Advice Help to Claim service offers tailored, practical support to help people make a Universal Credit claim up to receiving their first full correct payment on time, and is available online, on the phone and face-to-face through local Citizen’s Advice services.</p><p> </p><p>Although the Department offers comprehensive support for claimants to use our digital service, there will be occasions when people are unable to make their claim online, and so telephone applications can be accepted. In these instances, information normally available through a claimant’s online account, will be communicated in an alternative format which is best suited to an individual’s circumstances.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince","5094 ; 5095 ; 5098","2019-10-29T16:42:10.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156214/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156214/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-24","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans she has to update the information on gov.uk that universal credit must be claimed online to include reference to non-digital or telephone claims.","false","Biography information for Laura Pidcock","North West Durham","Laura Pidcock","5097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156215","Treasury","false","2019-10-29","<p>We do not comment on the Royal Mint’s production lead times as this is commercially sensitive information.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2019-10-29T13:49:39.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156215/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156215/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-24","Coinage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many 50 pence coins commemorating the UK leaving the EU have been minted as of 24 October 2019.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","4938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156216","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-31","<p>Departmental officials met with representatives of the Children’s Commissioner in October 2019 and will continue work with the Children’s Commissioner’s Office as part of engagement with other statutory bodies to address challenges involved in improving transparency of expenditure data.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-10-31T11:43:02.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156216/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156216/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-24","Speech and Language Therapy: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the report of the Children's Commissioner entitled We need to talk: Access to speech and language therapy, published in June 2019, what plans he has to ensure that spending on speech and language therapy services can be tracked at the (a) local and (b) national level.","false","Biography information for Geraint Davies","Swansea West","Geraint Davies","4912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156217","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-29","<p>The Department takes seriously the need to support vulnerable claimants, and wants the application process for Universal Credit to be as quick and easy as possible, ensuring that claimants receive money at the earliest opportunity. It is designed to be a ‘digital-first’ service, ensuring we make best use of technology to deliver a modern and effective working-age welfare system, allowing our staff to concentrate on those people who require additional support.</p><p> </p><p>We are already committed to placing Universal Credit guidance in the House’s Library and last updated it on 28 March 2019.</p><p> </p><p>Our Universal Credit Claimant Survey, found that 98 per cent of claimants have internet access and did claim online, and the majority of those said they found the claim process overall to be straightforward. This can be accessed at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-credit-full-service-claimant-survey" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-credit-full-service-claimant-survey</a></p><p> </p><p>All Jobcentre Plus offices across the country have Wi-Fi and computers available for claimants to access the internet. For those that are still unable to access or use digital services, or are not able to travel, assistance to make and maintain their claim is available via the Freephone Universal Credit helpline – which is clearly displayed on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p>Citizens Advice and Citizens Advice Scotland have been delivering the ‘Help to Claim’ service on a pilot basis since April 2019. The Citizens Advice Help to Claim service offers tailored, practical support to help people make a Universal Credit claim up to receiving their first full correct payment on time, and is available online, on the phone and face-to-face through local Citizen’s Advice services.</p><p> </p><p>Although the Department offers comprehensive support for claimants to use our digital service, there will be occasions when people are unable to make their claim online, and so telephone applications can be accepted. In these instances, information normally available through a claimant’s online account, will be communicated in an alternative format which is best suited to an individual’s circumstances.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince","5094 ; 5095 ; 5097","2019-10-29T16:42:10.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156217/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156217/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-24","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether written information on managing non-digital and telephone claims is (a) sent by post and (b) read over the telephone to universal credit claimants.","false","Biography information for Laura Pidcock","North West Durham","Laura Pidcock","5098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156218","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-10-29","<p>In the Legal Support Action plan published in February 2019 the Government committed to increase the scope for legal aid in family law cases to cover all Special Guardianship Orders in private family law cases; and removing the means test for those with parental responsibility to oppose placement or adoption orders in family law proceedings.</p><p> </p><p>To support those with family law problems who are not in scope for Legal Aid the government is doubling the funding for the Litigants in Person Support Strategy to £3m for the next two years, to ensure those representing themselves in court understand the process and are better supported through it.</p>","Aldridge-Brownhills","Wendy Morton",,"2019-10-29T17:41:59.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156218/answer","Biography information for Wendy Morton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156218/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-24","Legal Opinion: Parents and Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans his Department has for the future funding of independent legal advice for (a) parents and (b) kinship carers involved in the child welfare and family justice system after April 2020.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","5045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156219","Cabinet Office","false","2019-10-29","<p>Recognition of Trade Union bodies is a matter for the relevant employers to determine. The Government Property Agency works with its Facilities Management providers to ensure effective engagement of both parties in cases where recognition has not yet been achieved.</p><p>Contracts also set out agreement that the Principles of Good Employment Practice (as published by the Cabinet Office) will apply in regarding the employee engagement. A key principle of this is:</p><p>“Government recognises the premise that engagement between employee, employer and a recognised trade union where appropriate can be a key to unlocking productivity and creating a motivated workforce that feels respected, involved, heard, is well led and valued by those they work for and with.</p><p> </p>","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart",,"2019-10-29T16:39:19.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156219/answer","Biography information for Simon Hart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156219/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-10-24","Government Property Agency: Public and Commercial Services Union","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans the  Government Property Agency has to recognise the PCS union for its facility management contracts.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","5022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156220","Home Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>The total number of fire safety audits and the number of unsuccessful audits carried out by fire and rescue services (FRSs) in each year since 2010/11 are available in table FIRE1202 (link below). Information prior to 2010/11 is not available on a consistent basis.</p><p>This summer for the first time the Home Office collected information on the number of staff employed by FRSs for fire safety activities. The information can be found in FS10 in FIRE1204 (link below). This showed that in England on 31 March 2019 there were 72 fire engineers (Full Time Equivalent) employed by FRSs, 503 staff competent to carry out a short audit, 951 competent to carry out an audit, 597 competent to serve an enforcement notice and 407 competent to serve a prohibition notice. As FRS staff are likely to be competent to carry out more than one of these activities, the categories are not mutually exclusive.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables#fire-prevention-and-protection" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables#fire-prevention-and-protection</a></p><p>The Home Office does not collect information on the number of automated fire suppression systems installed by fire and rescue services.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","4930 ; 4931 ; 4932","2019-11-05T14:08:35.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156220/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156220/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-24","Fire Extinguishers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many automated fire suppression systems have been installed by each Fire Brigade in England in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","4939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156221","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-29","<p>The Department fully understands that maintaining access to hormone replacement therapy (HRT) medications is vitally important to many people in this country.</p><p>We are aware of ongoing supply issues with some HRT preparations due to manufacturing issues. We have been working closely with all suppliers of HRT preparations to maintain overall supply to patients.</p><p>We continue to work with all stakeholders to ensure relevant information about the HRT products affected by supply issues and the products that remain available is shared across the National Health Service on a regular basis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill",,"2019-10-29T17:42:24.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156221/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156221/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-24","Hormone Replacement Therapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he his taking to ensure the adequacy of availability of hormone replacement therapy medicines.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","4918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156222","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-29","<p>The Government is taking robust action and will introduce national standards with Statutory Taxi and Private Hire Vehicle Safeguarding Guidance, standardised checks, and enhanced enforcement. We will also pursue a national database. We intend to set out shortly these national standards which will safeguard passengers by monitoring adoption levels and engaging with authorities that do not follow them.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2019-10-29T17:27:34.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156222/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156222/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-24","Taxis: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to bring forward legislative proposals to reform taxi and private hire licensing laws; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","5072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156223","Home Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>Biometric data, a facial image only for EEA nationals and Facial Image and Fingerprints for Non-EEA nationals, for persons who hold Settled Status will be retained in accordance with the answer of 10 December 2018 HL11784 and in alignment with the Border Immigration and Citizenship Privacy notice.</p><p>A settled status holder is reliant on being able to prove they have status indefinitely and may at any time in the future, when they are eligible, make an application for citizenship, in which identity checks to confirm they are correct holder of status will be performed.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2019-11-05T12:37:17.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156223/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156223/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-24","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 10 December 2018 to HL11784, whether biometric data from people who have obtained settled status will not be retained.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","5092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156224","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-29","<p>Information on how many non-disclosure agreements the National Health Service has entered into with NHS staff in each of the last five years is not held centrally.</p><p>Non-disclosure agreements are settlement agreements that includes some form of confidentiality requirement that applies to one or both parties. Confidentiality clauses used appropriately can have a right and proper place but should go no further than is necessary to protect the legitimate interests of both the employer and the worker. Any cause in settlement agreement or contract of employment which purports to prevent an individual from making a protected disclosure, speaking about patient survey, quality of care or other wrong doing that is in the public interest has no place in the NHS and in any event would have no legal effect.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-10-29T12:42:41.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156224/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156224/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-24","NHS: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many non-disclosure agreements have been placed on NHS staff by NHS England in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","5093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156225","Home Office","false","2019-11-01","<p>Allegations of immigration abuse submitted by the public to the Home Office are received and managed by Immigration Enforcement.</p><p>Data on the number of staff employed to perform this task is available form 2016 when bespoke receipt and evaluation teams were introduced.</p><p>In the years since 2016 they have employed the following personnel to perform that task.</p><p>2016 – 57, 2017 – 63, 2018 – 59 and 2019 – 61.</p><p> </p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-11-01T12:45:32.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156225/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156225/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-24","UK Visas and Immigration: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people the National Allegations Team of UK Visas and Immigration has employed in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Sir Paul Beresford","Mole Valley","Sir Paul Beresford","4902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156226","Department for Education","false","2019-10-30","<p>Prisoners set to be released within 6 years have been eligible for tuition fee loans with the consent of the prison authorities. There are no plans to change this policy.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2019-10-30T19:41:06.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156226/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156226/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-24","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment he has made of extending student loan eligibility to people in prison who have more than six years to run on their sentence.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","4940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156227","Home Office","false","2019-11-01","<p>Information on the number of reports of immigration abuse received by the Home Office is published in our transparency data at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/collection/migration-transparency-data" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/collection/migration-transparency-data</a>.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-11-01T11:32:37.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156227/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156227/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-24","Immigration: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many complaints her Department has received on immigration fraud in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Sir Paul Beresford","Mole Valley","Sir Paul Beresford","4903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156228","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-11-01","<p>Following the changes we made to the recruitment process and eligibility criteria for probation officers there have been increases in both the volume and diversity of probation officer applicants. A national campaign to recruit probation officers was conducted earlier this year with new officers starting in July. As of 30 June 2019 there were 614 FTE Trainee Probation Officers in post.</p><p> </p><p>There were 3,357 FTE band 4 probation officers in post as at 30 June 2019. This figure represents a broadly steady trend. Regular figures on staffing in the NPS are released on Gov.uk;</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/national-offender-management-service-workforce-statistics</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-11-01T12:22:59.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156228/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156228/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-24","Probation: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps his Department is taking to recruit more probation officers.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156229","Home Office","false","2019-11-01","<p>All allegations of immigration abuse submitted by the public to the Home Office are carefully considered and are subjected to investigation. Cost restrictions prevent a detailed breakdown of specifically what action has been taken.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-11-01T12:34:34.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156229/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156229/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-24","Immigration: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many complaints on immigration fraud UK Visas and Immigration has investigated since 2009.","false","Biography information for Sir Paul Beresford","Mole Valley","Sir Paul Beresford","4904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156230","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-11-01","<p>We have not made any decisions on whether the new prisons as part of the Prime Minister’s announcement to build an additional 10,000 places will be operated by either the public or private sector. Decisions on the future management of these prisons will be announced in due course.</p><p> </p><p>This Government remains committed to a mixed market in operating custodial services in England and Wales.</p><p> </p><p>We believe that competition can deliver improvements to service quality, encourage innovation, secure capital investment, and achieve value for money.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-11-01T12:27:22.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156230/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156230/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-24","Full Sutton Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the new prison at Full Sutton will be operated by the public or private sector.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156231","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-10-29","<p>During periods of when prisoners are unlocked from their cell, the number of staff on each residential unit will be, in part determined by ‘Safe, Decent and Secure Operating Levels’ (SDSOLs) which are agreed in each establishment. A number of factors influence SDSOLs such as design and size of a residential unit, and specialist function or prisoner cohort.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to the SDSOLs, prison officers are being recruited across England and Wales as part of the Offender Management in Custody model (OMiC) - a vital part of our work to make prisons safer - and to support youth justice reform.</p><p> </p><p>We have invested significantly in increase staff numbers, recruiting an additional 4,366 (full time equivalent) prison officers between October 2016 and June 2019, surpassing our original target of 2,500. The majority of newly recruited prison officers are already on the landings and the recruitment drive will continue until we reach required levels across the prison estate, ensuring prisons can fulfil their purpose - protecting the public, rehabilitating offenders and crucially, reducing reoffending.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-10-29T15:14:56.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156231/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156231/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-24","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what ratio-based calculation is used by his Department to determine the necessary number of prison officers.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156232","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-11-01","<p>Information for October 2015 and October 2010 could only be obtained at disproportionate cost. I refer the Hon Member to PQ 165647 for repairs outstanding in 2010</p><p>As of October 2019 the current priority maintenance backlog totals approximately £900m. This is most up to date estimate we have of the costs associated with the maintenance backlog, inclusive of resource costs. This has increased from around £750m in 2018. The cost of the backlog increases each year owning largely to degradation of an aging estate.</p><p>This government has invested an additional £156m in 2020/21 to improve the conditions of existing prisons across the estate and underpin our commitment to a system that is decent, safe and secure.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-11-01T14:53:49.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156232/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156232/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-24","Prisons: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the backlog in prison maintenance (a) on 24 October 2019, (b) in October 2018, (c) in October 2015 and (d) in October 2010.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156233","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-11-01","<p>Routinely, the MoJ monitors capacity via prisoner places, rather than prison cells. This is to account for the variation in the type and size of cells across the estate.</p><p> </p><p>As of October 2019 approximately 760 cells, against a Certified Normal Accommodation figure of 78,989, were identified as out of use across the estate as a result of maintenance, including reactive maintenance, planned maintenance projects, security concerns or as a result of vandalism.</p><p> </p><p>Changes in the way data is collated in recent years means we cannot offer figures for 2010, 2015 and 2018.</p><p> </p><p>This government has invested an additional £156m in 2020/21 to improve the conditions of existing prisons across the estate and underpin our commitment to a system that is decent, safe and secure.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-11-01T12:30:50.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156233/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156233/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-24","Prisons: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the number and proportion of prison cells out of commission because of poor maintenance (a) on 24 October 2019, (b) in October 2018, (c) in October 2015 and (d) in October 2010.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156234","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-11-01","<p>We have been working closely with the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) to improve access to Universal Credit for prisoners and prison leavers. We are exploring a range of options to improve the claims process and DWP has piloted a number of changes that will support offenders making claims prior to release.</p><p> </p><p>One area that the pilots highlighted was the important role that dedicated DWP Prison Work Coaches play in our prison system to ensure access to Universal Credit. We continue to work with DWP to help support these work coaches, and to ensure they have both the right physical environment and access to the prisoners they need for efficient working.</p><p> </p><p>In July 2019, we committed to ongoing collaboration in this area through the publication of our National Partnership Agreement with DWP, which sets out clear roles and responsibilities for each department in getting prisoners into work and access to benefits.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-11-01T12:34:48.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156234/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156234/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-24","Prisoners: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to ensure that prisoners can apply for universal credit before release.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156235","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-10-30","<p>The MoJ regards well-managed contracts as fundamental to the proper functioning of the justice system, and a vital part of court and prison reform plans. The MoJ’s contract management teams closely monitor providers to ensure they fulfil their contractual commitments to maintain service delivery and value for money.</p><p>The Department conducts monthly assessments of the performance of its high priority contracts using a high-level scorecard. The scorecard assesses the performance of these contracts along 8 key themes:</p><ul><li>Contractual Compliance;</li><li>Contract Management Processes;</li><li>Finance;</li><li>Operations;</li><li>Risk;</li><li>Disputes;</li><li>Supplier views; and</li><li>Customer views.</li></ul>","Croydon South","Chris Philp",,"2019-10-30T15:24:54.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156235/answer","Biography information for Chris Philp","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156235/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-24","Ministry of Justice: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what data his Department holds on the performance of companies with which his Department holds contracts against key performance indicators.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156236","Home Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>Since 2014, when records were centralised, Immigration Enforcement has undertaken 6 criminal prosecutions into asylum fraud.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-11-05T16:00:04.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156236/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156236/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-24","Asylum: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many of the UKVI investigations into asylum fraud since 2009 have resulted in criminal prosecutions.","false","Biography information for Sir Paul Beresford","Mole Valley","Sir Paul Beresford","4905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156237","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-10-30","<p>Our hard-working officers play a crucial role in keeping prisons safe and transforming offenders’ lives, and ultimately make sure the public is protected.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise the need to recruit and retain staff to keep our prisons secure. We have invested significantly in increase staff numbers, recruiting an additional 4,366 (full time equivalent) prison officers between October 2016 and June 2019, surpassing our original target of 2,500. We will continue to recruit officers to ensure prisons are safe and decent.</p><p> </p><p>We’re giving staff the tools they need to do the job safely – rolling out PAVA incapacitant spray, and investing £100m to bolster security, in addition to £70 million announced previously, to fund tough airport-style security that will clamp down on the illicit items which fuel violence and hinder rehabilitation.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-10-30T15:31:29.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156237/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156237/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-24","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the number of prison officers.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156238","Home Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>Since 2014, when records were centralised, Immigration Enforcement has secured 3 convictions into asylum fraud.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-11-05T16:00:35.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156238/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156238/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-24","Immigration: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many of the UKVI-led prosecutions for immigration fraud since 2009 have resulted in convictions.","false","Biography information for Sir Paul Beresford","Mole Valley","Sir Paul Beresford","4906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156239","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-11-01","<p>Our initial estimate is that we will spend up to £280 million per year on contracted services under the future model of probation. This figure is subject to change as we refine the details of our plans and work with HM Treasury to agree sustainable funding arrangements.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-11-01T12:38:07.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156239/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156239/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-24","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of contracting out service delivery under the new probation system.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156240","Treasury","false","2019-10-31","<p>The UK has extensive global financial services ties with both leading advanced markets and emerging markets. When we leave the EU, we will have new tools at our disposal, which we will take advantage of to enhance our key financial services relationships. These include the chance to forge deep bilateral regulatory agreements based on equivalence and mutual recognition, and the opportunity to negotiate on financial services in Free Trade Agreements. We will also continue to use existing tools, such as engagement in the international standard setting bodies.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2019-10-31T17:07:42.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156240/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156240/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-24","Financial Services: International Cooperation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take steps to establish a new global platform agreement for financial services.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker","5016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156241","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-10-30","<p>We want prison officers to stay and progress their careers. We have improved induction processes to ease transition into the job, provide care and support for our staff and offer additional training. These measures are part of the work we are doing directly with Governors to address local issues and ensure experienced staff and new recruits remain in the service.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-10-30T15:37:44.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156241/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156241/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156241/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-24","Prison Officers: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of employment conditions for prison officers on retention of prison officers.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156242","Treasury","false","2019-10-29","<p>On 24 October 2019, following my meeting with Matt Hammerstein, CEO Barclays UK, Barclays announced that they will commit to full participation in the Post Office Banking Framework from the renewal date in early 2020, including maintaining the cash withdrawal facility using debit cards for Barclays customers.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has been clear that industry must play a key role in ensuring access to cash and banking services for people and businesses, and welcomes this decision which will continue to allow 95% of business and 99% of personal banking customers to carry out their everyday banking services at over 11,500 post offices across the UK.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2019-10-29T13:42:32.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156242/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156242/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156242/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-24","Barclays: Post Office","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 22 October 2019 to Question 1792, on Barclays: Post Office, what assessment he has made of the effect of Barclays Bank's planned withdrawal from the banking framework with Post Office Ltd on customers in rural areas who (a) do not have access to the internet, (b) are over 75 years old and (c) have accessibility needs.","false","Biography information for Jane Dodds","Brecon and Radnorshire","Jane Dodds","5116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156243","Department for International Trade","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Secretary of State recently visited the US, Australia, and Japan to meet her counterparts as well as British businesses and reiterated her commitment to free trade agreements (FTAs) with these countries.</p><p> </p><p>At the start of new FTA negotiations, the Government will publish its Outline Approach which will include our negotiating objectives and be accompanied by a scoping assessment which will be informed by economic modelling, setting out the potential economic impacts of any agreement.</p>","Bournemouth West","Conor Burns",,"2019-10-31T09:57:48.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156243/answer","Biography information for Conor Burns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156243/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156243/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-10-24","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment she has made of the potential economic merits of a trade deal between the UK and (a) the United States, (b) Australia and (c) Japan.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker","5017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156244","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-29","<p>Tildacerfont does not have a Marketing Authorisation for use in the United Kingdom and is not routinely available on the National Health Service. Tildacerfront is still in early development and is being studied for use in the treatment of patients with classic congenital adrenal hyperplasia. Once the trials with the product are complete, the drug manufacturer will be able to apply for a Marketing Authorisation.</p><p>Most new medicines are assessed by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) through its technology appraisal or highly specialised technologies programmes which make recommendations for the NHS on whether treatments represent an effective use of NHS resources. NHS commissioners are legally required to fund treatments recommended by NICE. If the manufacturer seeks a Marketing Authorisation for Tildacerfont, it will be considered through the established topic selection process to determine whether it should be assessed by NICE.</p><p>If Tildacerfont receives a Marketing Authorisation, funding decisions will be the responsibility of NHS commissioners, taking into account the available evidence and any relevant NICE recommendations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill",,"2019-10-29T17:42:53.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156244/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156244/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156244/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-24","Tildacerfont","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what plans he has to make Tildacerfont available on the NHS.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Dame Cheryl Gillan","4900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156245","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-29","<p>The Mail Opening Unit at Kidderminster meets it’s contracted performance requirements and there are no delays. There are full business continuity measures in place and these are regularly reviewed by the relevant officials.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2019-10-29T16:41:48.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156245/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156245/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156245/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-24","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment she has made of the potential effect of delays at the ENGIE Document Scanning facility at Kidderminster on benefit claimants.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","4928"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156246","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-29","<p>DWP Ministers and officials regularly meet with organisations representing members of the armed forces community, including veterans. Many of the veterans’ organisations work directly with the Jobcentre network to offer a range of specialist advice and help to veterans and family members who are in receipt of benefits. Those leaving the services are able to receive support to secure employment in a number of ways, including through the Career Transition Partnership (CTP). (The CTP can provide resettlement support, career transition advice and training opportunities.) DWP also gives veterans early voluntary entry to the Health and Work Programme if they wish.</p><p> </p><p>Veterans generally do well in securing employment once they have left the forces. Working age UK Armed Forces veterans residing in Great Britain were as likely to be employed (79% for both groups) as the comparable non-veteran population. <em>(Source - Annual Population Survey: UK Armed Forces veterans residing in Great Britain 2017.)</em> And 84% of the 2017/18 UK regular service leavers who used CTP services and reported their employment outcomes were employed within six months of leaving the Service. <em>(Source: Career Transition Partnership Annual Statistic: UK Regular Service personnel Employment 1 April 2013 to 31 March 2019.) </em></p><p> </p><p>DWP has traditionally collected some information on claims from veterans through our Labour Market System. As veterans claiming benefits increasingly receive Universal Credit rather than legacy benefits, we are looking to see what opportunities might be available to better identify and record veterans to help ensure they get the appropriate tailored help and support they need.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince","5090","2019-10-29T15:41:53.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156246/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156246/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156246/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-24","Veterans: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if she will conduct an assessment of the potential merits of (a) Job Centre and (b) Department for Work and Pensions staff collecting information on veterans on employment record systems.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","5089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156247","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-29","<p>DWP Ministers and officials regularly meet with organisations representing members of the armed forces community, including veterans. Many of the veterans’ organisations work directly with the Jobcentre network to offer a range of specialist advice and help to veterans and family members who are in receipt of benefits. Those leaving the services are able to receive support to secure employment in a number of ways, including through the Career Transition Partnership (CTP). (The CTP can provide resettlement support, career transition advice and training opportunities.) DWP also gives veterans early voluntary entry to the Health and Work Programme if they wish.</p><p> </p><p>Veterans generally do well in securing employment once they have left the forces. Working age UK Armed Forces veterans residing in Great Britain were as likely to be employed (79% for both groups) as the comparable non-veteran population. <em>(Source - Annual Population Survey: UK Armed Forces veterans residing in Great Britain 2017.)</em> And 84% of the 2017/18 UK regular service leavers who used CTP services and reported their employment outcomes were employed within six months of leaving the Service. <em>(Source: Career Transition Partnership Annual Statistic: UK Regular Service personnel Employment 1 April 2013 to 31 March 2019.) </em></p><p> </p><p>DWP has traditionally collected some information on claims from veterans through our Labour Market System. As veterans claiming benefits increasingly receive Universal Credit rather than legacy benefits, we are looking to see what opportunities might be available to better identify and record veterans to help ensure they get the appropriate tailored help and support they need.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince","5089","2019-10-29T15:41:53.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156247/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156247/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156247/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-24","Veterans: Unemployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what discussions she has had with veterans' organisations on recent trends in the rate of unemployed veterans.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","5090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156248","Home Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>The Home Office does not routinely publish data to answer this question.</p><p>Whilst we hold data on the current addresses of asylum claimants, data on how many asylum seekers resident in Scotland have been required to attend Home Office appointments in England as part of their asylum application; on how many occasions those applicants did not attend those appointments; and how many asylum seekers that failed to attend a Home Office appointment in England when they were resident in Scotland had their asylum application refused in each of the last five calendar years, could only be obtained at disproportionate costs.</p><p>The Home Office does routinely publish data on the number of applications for asylum refused in the UK in each of the last five years, broken down by nationality, in its quarterly Immigration Statistics release, the latest release published on 22<sup>nd</sup> August 2019.</p><p>Latest edition available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-year-ending-june-2019/list-of-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-year-ending-june-2019/list-of-tables</a></p><p> </p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-11-05T15:01:23.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156248/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156248/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156248/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-24","Asylum: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to Question 281779 on Asylum: Scotland, how many asylum seekers resident in Scotland have been required to attend Home Office appointments in England as part of their asylum application; on how many occasions those applicants did not attend those appointments; and how many asylum seekers that failed to attend a Home Office appointment in England when they were resident in Scotland had their asylum application refused in each of the last five calendar years.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","5048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156249","Home Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>As part of the asylum process, asylum seekers are expected to attend Home Office appointments such as screening interviews and substantive asylum interviews.</p><p>Individuals receiving asylum support are provided with travel cards, or are reimbursed accordingly, to ensure they can attend their Home Office appointments without financial detriment.</p><p>As part of the registration process, no provision is made for funding in advance of the registration. If an asylum seeker is destitute or vulnerable, they can present themselves to Migrant Help who may assist with access to travel.</p><p>We are committed to ensuring that asylum claims are considered without unnecessary delay. Asylum Operations are currently exploring several initiatives to improve the asylum application process to provide a better service to claimants.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-11-05T15:08:08.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156249/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156249/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156249/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-24","Asylum: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to Question 281780 tabled on 24 July 2019 on Asylum: Scotland, what assessment she has made of the (a) financial and (b) other barriers faced by asylum seekers that are resident in Scotland required to attend Home Office appointments in England as part of their asylum application.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","5049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156250","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-29","<p>The Department is continuing to work closely with NHS England, NHS Improvement, Public Health England and local Government to ensure there is a seamless transition to routine commissioning of pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) upon culmination of the PrEP Impact trial. We will set out how the programme will be funded very shortly.</p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","5074","2019-10-29T17:40:43.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156250/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156250/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156250/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-24","HIV Infection: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what progress is being made on making PrEP available on the NHS.","true","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","5073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156251","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-29","<p>The Department is continuing to work closely with NHS England, NHS Improvement, Public Health England and local Government to ensure there is a seamless transition to routine commissioning of pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) upon culmination of the PrEP Impact trial. We will set out how the programme will be funded very shortly.</p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","5073","2019-10-29T17:40:43.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156251/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156251/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156251/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-24","HIV Infection: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to ensure the routine commissioning of PrEP on the NHS.","true","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","5074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156252","Cabinet Office","false","2019-10-29","<p>The Government Property Agency's Total Facilities Management is carried out by Interserve FM Ltd and I refer the Hon member to the answers provided in PQ 214493 answered on 4th Feb 2019.</p>","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart",,"2019-10-29T16:40:38.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156252/answer","Biography information for Simon Hart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156252/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156252/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-10-24","Government Property Agency: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government Property Agency's Total Facilities Management Contract requires (a) staff to be paid the  Living Wage set by the  Living Wage Foundation and (b) London-based staff to be paid the London Living Wage set by the Greater London Authority.","true","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","5077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156253","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Access for All programme provides accessibility improvements over and above those required by the industry. Stations are selected for this funding against a range of criteria including annual footfall, the incidence of disability in the area, and the availability of third party funding for the project. We also take into account local factors such as proximity to a hospital. Stations are also chosen to ensure a fair geographical spread of projects across the country.</p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2019-10-31T12:28:41.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156253/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156253/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156253/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-24","Railway Stations: Access","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what criteria his Department uses to assess which train stations are eligible for disabled access upgrade.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","5087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156254","Department for Transport","false","2019-11-01","<p>The Government is taking robust action and will introduce National Minimum Standards including mandatory disability awareness training when Parliamentary time allows. In 2020 we plan to consult on revised best practice guidance for local licensing authorities, including strengthened recommendations on the provision of disability awareness training for drivers.</p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2019-11-01T13:41:36.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156254/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156254/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156254/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-24","Taxis: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his Department's timescale is for bringing forward legislation to ensure that disability equality training for taxi drivers becomes mandatory.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","5088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156255","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-29","<p>As announced on 30 September £100 million of seed funding has been made available to support 21 major projects to commence their development of schemes to be delivered in a second phase of major hospital rebuilds (HIP2).</p><p>This £100 million of seed funding will be provided as capital and will enable project teams, specialist advisers and site surveys. The funding will be drawn by providers in line with need up to 1% of the estimated capital value of each HIP2 scheme. The budget has been received for 2020-21 and 2021-22 financial years but funding this year could be available if there is an immediate and strong case. NHS England and NHS Improvement will be visiting the schemes to discuss their proposals and how they can be helped to develop.</p><p>Trusts will be required to provide a breakdown of what seed funding will be spent on and how that will accelerate the project development. The Department and NHS England and NHS Improvement will then ascertain how much seed funding will be provided for each scheme.</p><p>Seed funding will not constitute approval of the scheme as a whole as that will be subject to further development and subject to the usual business case approvals process, including demonstrating affordability and value for money.</p><p> </p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar","4954","2019-10-29T14:48:34.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156255/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156255/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1156255/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-24","Imperial College Healthcare NHS Trust: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much of the seed funding announced on 30 September 2019 will be allocated to (a) Charing Cross Hospital, (b) Hammersmith Hospital and (c) St Mary's Hospital, Paddington.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","4953"
